data.name: label1.Text
data.value:
You can run this wizard at any time to help you set up your Remote Potato server and get connected to it over the Internet.
Do you want to enable security? If you do this, you will need to enter a username and password when connecting to your server.

data.name: lblRouterBlurb.Text
data.value:
Remote Potato has checked and Internet connections are not getting through to this computer from outside your home network.
The most likely reason is that your router has to be set up to allow this. ('port forwarding') Remote Potato can try to automatically set up your router for you using UPnP technology.
You may skip this step if you prefer to set up your router manually later, if your router doesn't support UPnP or if you won’t be using Remote Potato over the Internet.
If unsure, answer 'Yes'.

data.name: lblDNSblurb.Text
data.value:
To connect to Remote Potato away from your home, you need to tell your web browser (or mobile device) how to locate your home network on the Internet.
The simplest way is to use your external IP address. At the moment, this is **EXTERNAL-IP**
However, with some ISPs, this IP address can change, so it can be useful to use a free 'Dynamic DNS' service which allows you to choose your own URL (web address) instead, which is always kept up-to-date with the Internet address of your home network.
How would you like to access Remote Potato over the Internet?

data.name: label20.Text
data.value: 1. Close this wizard, then choose your favourite media folders and (if you use Media Center) TV channels. 2. Start the Remote Potato Server using the big button at the top left of the main window. 3. Connect! You can use any web browser to connect to Remote Potato, or an app for iPhone, Android or Windows Phone or tablet. See 'Live TV Front End' for examples on how to connect to your server from different clients.
